title: Free Range Printer Raspberry Pi Box

description.text: I am making a Raspberry Pi powered Printer using an Epson TM-T88III receipt printer, which is a receipt printer that you can get from eBay fairly cheaply. As a part of the project, I wanted a box to sit under the printer and hold the Raspberry Pi so that the printer and Pi can sit neatly, and be used in a business environment. The two projects I am using it for are (1) to print receipts when pizza orders come into an OSCommerce-based web site, and (2) as a Free Range Printer (https://github.com/andrewn/raspi-printer). I'm sharing the box, as it'll be useful to anyone using Raspberry Pi-based printing. It's customizable so you can put in the size of the box, to match your printer, and you can have an LED mounting hole (or not). I also include STL files of a box that matches the Epson TM-T88III, since that's the printer I used. But the design should work with any receipt printer.

Print the base and cover pieces.  They are large, so make sure you orient them so they are flat side down and rotated to fit your print bed. They have bevels so you can pry them up using a flat edge fairly easily.  
Slide the Raspberry Pi into the clips in the base, which will hold it in the middle of the box, with the ethernet jack facing the cutout in the back. The clips are pretty secure, so you'll need to use a slot head screwdriver to pop the Pi into place. The design leaves room on all sides for various cables, SD card, etc. If you have an LED, slide it into the tube facing the front, and tape it in place if needed. I also needed a voltage convertor (the Pi runs at 3.3v, the TM-T88 serial port runs at 5v), which I attached to one side using double stick tape.  
There's a pic of the interior, so you can see how things are arranged.  
There's an option to generate standoffs, which will fit into the mounting holes in more recent Raspberry Pi's.  
When the Pi and all cabling is connected, check that everything works, then route the cables out the back cutout. Slide the cover over the base until it is snug. Stick the printer on top.  
For extra credit, stick rubber feed on the corners of the base.  
You're done!

description.text:
I've decided to try an experiment. I realized that many of the textures used for my floors would make fantastic bases for miniatures. I decided to create this set to see if there was interest in having textured bases. In the past, I've used the excellent products from Micro Art Studio. They have many beautiful bases, each with a ton of variations at the same size, while also offering the same base styles in many different sizes. This helps make a warband or even a set of minis for RPG have a nice sense of variety while still tying them together thematically.

I've looked for bases on thingiverse, and what I found is that there are many great bases, but for the most part they have few or no variants at the same size, or few or no size variants. With this broader set, I've created over 200 variants, across over 3 different sizes. I've covered every game I have even passing familiarity with in the broader set, such as D&D, Warhammer 40k, Age of Sigmar, Pathfinder, Malifaux, Infinity, Guildball and Warmachine/Hordes. If there's a base variant under 100mm used by a game that isn't available in these sets, please let me know so I can add it, but also add it to all future miniature base releases.

When printing, you want to make the base look the best possible for the miniature you are putting on it that you almost certainly put tons of hard work into. For that reason, on any FDM printer (a printer that uses plastic filament), I strongly recommend that you print the upright versions of the bases, as the detail on the z axis is so much greater then the detail on the x/y axes. If you are using a resin printer, you can print the horizontal versions and get a great result. When printing the upright bases, you will have to glue them, and probably do a little work with a putty do deal with the seam.

description.text:
The objects shown were created via OpenSCAD scripts which were generated by JavaScript .

http://kitwallace.co.uk/3d/braidmaker.html

This performs braiding of an NxM grid, with added holes, and provides output as SVG or OpenSCAD. For a complete grid, braiding creates gcd(N,M) separate links or ropes. Thus if N and M are relatively prime, braiding is done with a single rope, while a square grid NxN requires N ropes.

The OpenSCAD code generally works but sometimes encounters problems with intersecting polyhedra. I've printed the 2x2 braid ( the link L4a1 or Solomon's knot) on the Bristol Hackspace's Reprap with a large brim and support but failed with lack of base adhesion with larger versions. Suggestions welcome.

The SVG output can be useful for laser-cutting.

There is more about the algorithm in my blog http://kitwallace.tumblr.com/post/167911772809/generating-braids-with-javascript

structure consists of a single tube profile formed using 3 swept bodies ( the large outer loop and the two smaller internal loops). description.text:
I bought a bike recently. One of the previous owners did not like the stock levers and replaced them with these $22 Ali Express ones (I dislike cheap aftermarket levers). The levers are fine but they came partially assembled from the most recent owner (the adjustable extension was unattached, leaving 2-finger shorty levers).
The levers have a dovetailed extension that is anchored with a single hex bolt; the bolt does not strike the red material first, it strikes the grey material first, so even with a washer it does not bite the red lever extension properly.
After going to ACE and getting the correct bolts and some washers, I just gave up and decided to fix them with 3D printing. Moments like these are when I LOVE 3D printing.
The PETG inserts press-fit snugly into the recessed area and the bolt hole lines up perfectly with the threaded hole in the gray part of the lever. There is minimal force in the horizontal direction, and the dovetail bears most/all of the pulling force anyway; we'll see how they hold up.

description.text:
Credit for this idea goes to sniperKE. He wanted a cake mold based on my rendition of the (in)famous ‘Pile of Poo’ emoji. This works pretty well because when cutting the model in half, the front part can more or less be modeled with a single mold (after making some small tweaks).

I have also made a flatter mold more suitable for making cookies, by request from earendilin.

You can use this to make cakes, cookies, pastry, or other moldable things like sand sculptures in the shape of this internet phenomenon. Of course, if you're going to make food with this, ensure to use a food-safe printer setup and filament.

The unscaled size of the cake/cookie is about 7 by 7 cm (2.75 by 2.75 inch), with the cookie being about 17 mm (2/3 inch) thick, and the cake 35 mm (1.4 inch). Of course you can scale the molds to larger or smaller sizes in your slicer program.

To facilitate getting the cake/cookie out of the mold, rub it with a thin layer of butter or other grease, then coat this layer with flour before pressing the dough into the mold.
For sand sculptures, the sand must not be too humid, to allow for an easy release with no sand remaining stuck to the mold.

Anycubic Kossel Controller Box

This upgrade is designed to provide better cooling to the electronics by changing the mainboard's location. Furthermore, it mounts up to two MOSFET modules.

I designed this upgrade together with the PSU Box, which you can find here.

Why Did I Design This?

Especially when the Delta uses a heated bed, the electronics operate in a warmer environment. To avoid overheating and to mount the PSU when adding a heated bed, I chose to design a case for each of them and mount them on the back extrusion.

Features

  • Can be mounted in two distinct ways (see below).
  • Mounts the TriGorilla mainboard with access to both plugs.
  • Dimensions: 169x138x62 (depends on how it's mounted...).
  • Up to two MOSFET modules can be mounted.
  • Easily printable on the normal Anycubic Kossel without supports.
  • Stepper driver cooling with the help of the "Stepper Motor Aero Tunnel" by Facocero, which can be found here. However, my included fan adapter is necessary!

EDIT: This case is featured in my Anycubic Kossel Upgrades Video.

EDIT2: I've published another version of this case. Its height is reduced by 40mm, but it doesn't mount any MOSFET modules!

See below for a detailed installation guide!

Have fun with this model!

Assembly

The whole assembly relies on default M3-M5 hardware. If you lack some screws, a drill will be your best friend ;-)
You'll need:

  • 12x ≥8mm long M3 screws for the covers
  • ≥3x 8mm long M3 screws for the mainboard

  • ≥2x screws with corresponding T-Nuts, depending on the way you want to mount your case. (The holes should be fine for M4, if you want to use M5 you'd need to use a proper drill.)
  • 2x ~30 mm long M3 screws for fixing the fan adapter to the tunnel and case (optional)
  • 4x M3 screws for fixing the fan to the adapter

The case can be added to the Delta in two different ways:

  • On the back extrusion:

description.text:
This is a part designed to mount a BLTouch z-probe to the two M3 threaded holes found on the left side of the Flexion extruder coldbar. It is designed to minimize the (already large) x-offset from the primary nozzle to the probe tip, and properly position the probe in z per the most recent BLTouch smart docs. There is a notch cutout of the top/back of the part to allow clearance of the extruder cleaning brush.

It's designed for and tested with the Flexion dual kit for R1 clones; I don't have CAD files for the single or e3d versions to verify compatibility. Use M3x4 or M3x5 screws to attach - any longer and you risk running into the threading for the holes that mount the bar to the carriage.

The current version is designed for use on the left side of the cold bar - the tapped holes are machined such that the holes on the left and right ends are at different heights from each other, but remain at the same height whichever way you flip the bar for installation. I may design a right-hand side mount if there is interest, and a STEP file is included in the distribution to simplify remixing.

Because this is mounted to the extruder cold bar, the offset dimensions should be very precise with respect to the nozzle. Exact offsets will probably vary slightly due to printing process, and the z offset should certainly be measured for your setup, but these x and y offsets should be close to correct:

#define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -71  // X offset: -left  +right  [of the nozzle]
#define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 2    // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]

Notes:

Probably best to print in PETG, ABS, Nylon, or other thermally stable plastic. The cold bar end doesn't get hot to the touch, and I've used a PLA version in testing, but long-term stability is untested.

I recommend printing this part on its 'back' - that is, with the face that mounts to the cold bar against your print bed. This minimizes issues with the tiny islands otherwise formed as part of the cold bar mounting holes (see photo #3), and also minimizes any influence of layer height on the probe z-height.

You can probably get away with 200 µm layers, but I printed at 150 µm and smaller so that's the recommended resolution. Supports may not be required, depending on your ability to print overhangs and bridge, but I used them to make sure the slot clearance was maintained.

Cleanup

Remove supports, if used, and make sure that the screw clearance holes and nut pockets are clean and properly dimensioned. Pay special attention to the clearance slot for the cleaning brush - you want to remove any extra 'squish' from the first layer(s).

Mounting

  1. Mount this part to the Flexion cold bar (left side) using 2x M3x4 or M3x5 screws. Longer screws should not be used - they may interfere with the mounting screws that hold the cold bar to the x carriage.

    • Ensure the extruder's cleaning brush has adequate clearance in the brush slot. Properly printed, the brush should not make contact with the slot walls.
    • Ensure that the mounting screw heads do not protrude above the pockets designed into the mount for them. If they do, they may contact the probe and push it away from square.

  2. Mount the BLTouch probe to its 'shelf,' with the cables on the outside, using 2x M3 screws (M3x8 is about right) and 2x M3 nuts.

  3. Connect the probe to your printer controller and set up your firmware appropriately, as described in various BLTouch documentation.

Build & General Notes:

This is partially a print build, as well a woodworking build (if you can call a LACK wood...) and part mechanical/electrical, you may need to modify some parts depending on the direction you want to go and the materials you choose in the end.

My build instructions below are based on my configuration of one front door, hinged on the left side; if you want it hinged on the right or want multiple hinged doors adjust them as required (refer to the BOM's for a couple of configurations).

You will also need the following additional products:

  • 4x spare legs from the LACK table used as the base
  • 4x 24x18x0.080" acrylic sheets (i used Optix (by Plaskolite) from Lowes)
  • a number of 6-32x0.25" PC case screws
  • a number of no.6x3/4" self tapping screws (with the cut angular face)

If I was building this again I may may the following changes:

  • I might consider using the 0.20" acrylic sheet instead I'm not sure yet though as its twice the price, twice the weight, but a little more rigid. This top is cumbersome enough to lift/move, the added weight might make that much more difficult.
  • I built the sides to be locked in place, others use magnets to make them removable. I looked at it as since the whole top is removable why have the sides come off? I may go back and modify it slightly before I seal everything up and hinge the right side door as well, not sure yet.
Step 1. Cut all the things....

Its easiest to get all the cutting out of the way at once, then its just putting it all together, so...
Read thrice, measure twice, and cut once...

Legs:

  1. Take all 8 (4 from the top table and the 4 spare) LACK legs and using a tablesaw or cutoff saw cut the bottom 20mm off each leg to expose the hollow centre. Each leg should be 380mm long now.
  2. Take the 4 spare legs from those and measuring from the open end mark and cut them to 192mm long, this should leave you with 4 hollow leg tubes.

Acrylic:

  1. You need to cut the width down from 18" to 442mm (I know I'm mixing units)I opted to use a scribe and straightedge instead of the tablesaw, its just as fast for straight cuts and much less prone to chipping. If you haven't cut acrylic on a tablesaw before, you don't have a triple chip blade, or you don't have spare sheets I'd highly recommend going with the scribe method...
  2. mark 442mm on the protective plastic at the top and bottom, use a tee square and make sure the edge will be straight, tape in place.
  3. use a acrylic scribe and make a couple light passes to mark the line, then a couple harder ones to pull out/start the groove.
  4. take the straight edge away and make full pull passes off the edge of the sheet, flipping it around so you get both ends and cut a groove about 1/2 way through.
  5. gently bend/flex it on the edge, it should snap clean and easy, if it takes any force stop and make the groove deeper.
  6. for the door once you've cut the width you need to notch the two hinge corners out 4x40mm to clear the hinge, use the same method scribing/cutting a groove until it breaks through easily.

You should now have everything you need to put this all together, 4 longer legs, 4 cut down legs, 3 walls, and 1 door.

Step 2. Off/On with its legs...

Make the legs:

  1. You need the 4 Leg Couplers printed from the BOM for this step.
  2. Glue/insert one coupler in between each long top leg portion and shorter bottom leg portion to create a longer leg. I aligned the coupler with the layers parallel to the axis of the leg, there's a little bump on one face of each coupler to help you get it centered between the leg sections.
  3. Make sure they're fully pressed together and straight, I taped them to a couple straightedges until they dried.

You should now have 4x 572mm long legs, this will raise the top up to have open faces just over 24" tall so you don't need to cut the acrylic sheet down in height.

On & off with its legs:
You need:

  • the 4 appropriate top spacers from the BOM,
  • the 4 appropriate leg inserts from the BOM,
  • the 4 extended legs,
  • and 4 ikea leg screws.
    1. start threading the screw into the leg, put the top plate on the screw and screw the leg into the table until it just makes contact.
    2. figure out how many faces the plate needs to turn to be aligned when tight.
    3. back the plate/leg off together until you can rotate the plate to the needed orientation, tighten the two down together until tight.
    4. once you have the legs on you have a option here, you can glue the leg inserts into the legs, or what I did was drill 4 small holes through the leg into the insert, then I used some no6x3/4" screws to hold them in (incase I wanted to change things later).

You should now have a inverted table with 4 legs, and are one step closer...

Step 3. Walls, supports and fittings...

You need:

  • printed glass_edge_supports from the BOM,
  • the hinges & backers from the BOM,
  • the insert wall supports from the BOM,
  • 6x32x0.35" screws

Now the fun begins...

  1. with the table inverted place one edge support on the top near middle between the two legs, then stand a acrylic wall into it and the two corners.
  2. slide 2 more edge supports onto the two sides, they should get pinched between the acrylic wall and the legs.
  3. take the required insert supports and using a 6x32 screw place them over the acrylic wall corners and screw them lightly into the insert.
  4. adjust the edge supports so they're in the middle of the legs and "top", then mark their required locations.
  5. take the insert support screws out, take the wall out, take the edge supports and drill/screw them in place with no6 screws, or as I did, use double sided adhesive to hold them in place.
  6. slide the acrylic wall back into place, screw in the two insert supports, you should now have a completed side with the wall supported at 4 corners as well as 2 supports on the sides and one on the "top".
  7. repeat steps 1-6 for the other 2 solid walls.
Step 4. Add a Door...

You need:

  • printed hinges and backplates from the BOM,
  • the correct drill guide from the BOM,
  • screws, 6x32 & no6.
  1. using the drill guide, line it up on the leg where the top hinge will go and drill 3 small holes in the leg.
  2. line up the hinge, and using 3 no6 screws screw it into the leg. caution, the leg isn't that strong, its easy to strip the screw.
  3. take the other hinge, using 3 6x32 screws screw it into the leg insert.
  4. now the fun part... place the door panel in place, it should be behind the hinges, it helps to tape it a couple places loosly to hold it.
  5. adjust/line it up where you want it, I used paper shims on the 3 sides to get it to have a even space all the way around, at the "top" i used about the thickness of a business card on top of the supporting top plate which I then matched on the hinge side.
  6. swing the hinges over to line up where they should be on the panel, mark through the hinges the centres of the 6 holes, take it all apart.
  7. Drill the 6 holes through the door... Acrylic doesn't take much pressure to crack so the screws go through it, not into it, they will thread into the back plate. start with a small pilot drill and work your way up. One trick with acrylic and small holes is to put your drill in reverse instead, the friction heats the acrylic and the bit goes right through clean, then just the edge of a sharp knife to clean off the burr.
  8. pass 3 6x32 screws into each hinge, through the panel and thread them into the backplate. don't tighten them too tight, just snug, the door doesn't need too much support.
  9. attach the handle thing... when I figure out how I want to open/close/latch this door... dunno yet...
Step 5. Put it all together.

You should now have a completed enclosure top, last thing to do is stick it on the stack...
You need:

  • printed bottom post supports from the BOM,
  • no6 screws.
  1. use the drill guide to mark the 4 screws on each corner of the lower table that the printer sits on.
  2. pilot drill the holes on each corner.
  3. line up the bottom support as required, for where the hinge sits you can snap the little plate off if desired, the support is scored to allow that.
  4. screw them in place, keep the gap equal on all sides.

Done!
You should be able to turn the enclosure over and set it on the supports, they should align in the legs and keep everything straight.
Thats it, unless you want some finishing steps for this part I could include...

Step 6. Final Touches...

I haven't made it here yet myself, but this is what I plan to do:

  1. silicone (eventually) around the 3 closed sides to seal them up.
  2. add 0.25" rubber gasket tape on the three sides of the base along the bottom where the wall will be to seal it up.
  3. add a gasket of some sort to the door, still working this out...

Other add-ons, exhaust fans etc I'll be adding in later Lack Attack builds, they should be coming shortly.

description.text:
I liked very much the CR-10 Dual Z axis by Caster, also the Frame Braces from TomExplorador. So I decided to unite them, and I made some adjustements for the Tevo Tornado. To get the idea of the construction please read the original things, especially look at caster's page https://myfordboy.blogspot.de/p/the-cr10-has-single-z-axis-leadscrew.html .

You need following additional parts:
600mm leadscrew and nut https://goo.gl/fM8znL
GT2 852mm Timing Belt: https://goo.gl/iXa4sv
3 Bearings: https://goo.gl/HnzTqr (1 x idler, 2x right lead screw)
2 x M8 threaded rods
6 x M8 nuts
7 x M5 x 20 screws (idler and lower holder)
7 x M5 x 35 screws (upper holder and geanty plate)
11 x M5 Tee nuts
2 x M3 x 20 screws and nuts (bearing cover left)
4 x M3 x 15 screws and nuts (lead screw nut)
6 x M3 x 10 screws (pulleys)
1 x M2,5 x 10 screw and nut (cuff (manschette8mm.stl))
A few washers.

Following plastc you need more than once:
6 x BallNutM8
2 x 516_Nut (alternative 2 additional BalNutM8)
2 x pulley-64
3 x Spacer8-7mm (for mounting the gantry plate)
2 x Washer8 (right lead screw: between 64 tooth pulley and upper bearing and between cuff and lower ball-bearing)
2 x Z-RHL-75 (right side upper & lower holder)

For the left side you should use the 100mm holder, on the right side both 100mm and 75mm holder are possible, but the 75mm parts are more rigid.

For the gantry plate I used PETG, because it sees the most heat.
If you don't like to dismount the right Z wagon off the X axis, do it without the inner gantry plate screw, the gantry plate mounting with the 2 remaining screws should be strong enough.
The extruder of the Tevo tornado is higher than the one of the CR-10. If you don't like to loose some mm Z room, install the Tevo extruder turned 90° with the Titan_mount.

description.text:
This is a Key Tag in the shape of an owl that I made for my niece.

The interesting thing is that I did multiple colour changes (I have a single extruder/head).
I printed with 0.2mm layer height.


I use Octoprint to manage my printer so all I had to do was insert a M0 just before the start of the new colour's first layer. The table below shows when I changed. Note that I don't use a raft so I didn't need to allow for that.

Height    Before Layer    Changed to Colour
0mm Start Black
3mm 16 Grey
3.6mm 19 White
4.2mm 22 Red
4.8mm End N/A


I also have some GCODE scripts in my Octoprint settings which assist in colour changes during a "Pause". Here they are:

After print job is paused:

{% if pause_position.x is not none %}
; relative XYZ and Extrude
G91
M83
; retract 5 filament, move Z up 5mm
G1 Z+5 E-5 F4500 
; back to absolute XYZE
M82
G90
; move to a safe rest position (X100,Y100), adjust as necessary
G1 X100 Y100 
{% endif %}

Before print job is resumed:

G1 E5 F4500
G1 E5 F4500
; absolute E
M82
; absolute XYZ
G90
; reset E
G92 E{{ pause_position.e }}
; move back to pause position XYZ
G1 X{{ pause_position.x }} Y{{ pause_position.y }} Z{{ pause_position.z }} F4500
; reset to feed rate before pause if available
{% if pause_position.f is not none %}G1 F{{ pause_position.f }}{% endif %}
{% endif %}


Hope this was interesting/helpful.

In Late May 1997, an area of convection developed near the Marshall Islands, and rapidly became a low pressure area. On June 1, the low pressure area organized into a tropical depression. Nestor intensified into a category 1 typhoon on June 7, as it started to affect the Mariana Islands. Nestor continued to intensify, and on June 10, Nestor reached its peak intensity as a category 5 super typhoon, as the storm began to affect the Northern Mariana Islands. At this time, Nestor began showing annular characteristics. Nestor began to weaken slowly, as typical annular typhoons do, while it developed an eye measuring 65 kilometers across. On June 15, Nestor transitioned into an extra-tropical cyclone, as it weakened.

Felix formed from a tropical wave on August 31, passing through the southern Windward Islands on September 1 before strengthening to attain hurricane status. license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a simple slide-on sleeve for a CZ P-09 9mm magazine allowing it to fit a CZ P-07 without over-insertion. Top of sleeve is fairly close to the outer dimensions of the P-07 grip at the bottom.

This SHOULD work with a P10c, however the sleeve will not match the bottom of the grip as well in the front. Once I get my hands on a new P-09 magazine with the P10c cut I will update.

There are three models. The first is a very simple block that has no extra grip surfaces.

The 'A' model has a large 30 degree serrations to make it easier to remove the mag if it becomes stuck, however when I print it in PLA the edges aren't very sharp or grippable. YMMV.

Model 'B' has a spherical indentation on either side allowing for a good purchase on the stock floor plate. Depending on how you configure your slicer, you may want to consider adding supports since the depth of the indentation is almost all the way through the side panel. Best results have come from printing it upside down with supports. This is really the one I recommend.

Printed in PLA on the Prusa I3 Mk2 with the 3.1.0 firmware (linear advance) at both 0.2mm and 0.05mm. Because this is a simple model there is very little outward difference in the surface finish regardless of layer height, so it is recommended you prioritize layer adhesion over appearance when adjusting your slicer.

NOTE: This is similar to the sleeve you might see with an M&P Shield in that there is nothing securing it to the magazine aside from friction. Future versions may replace the base plate and be more secure, but issues of printing to avoid layer-separation with repeated use will need to be addressed first. Knowing this, it is NOT recommended that this be used for anything beyond range experimentation, particularly since your own print set-up may produce different results.

This is not a quick print (mine took 4 hours) and it is very near to the maximum size that the bed will take. I actually rotated it by 45 degrees when I came to print, so it was diagonal on my printer bed - that way the skirt stays on the bed. If you do that and also leave the infill at the 45 degree default then it actually prints the infill in line with the edges, which I quite like but you might prefer to change that.

I wanted to make my printer look a bit neater, so I looked on here for covers for the control board and only found one for an earlier model which had cutouts in the wrong places for my connections (but if I'd searched better then I would have found https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2252634). So I designed this one. It is a single piece and it prints upside down so it has no overhangs or bridges except for the ends of the ventillation slots. I tried to put a lot of ventillation slots in the cover, even though my board doesn't seem to get that warm - that maybe the English climate! The "TRONXY" in the cover is also for ventilation mainly.

After fixing my circuit board on the spacers with the M3 nuts, I then fitted 20mm nylon stand-offs because I was just going to put a flat sheet over the circuit using them. But once you have a 3d printer then you can't settle for that! My cover is fixed onto the stand-offs.

I designed this in OpenSCAD and I have included the source file so that people who wish it was different can make it so. I made mine with 1.5mm thick walls (as in the accompanying STL) but it is actually a parameter in the SCAD file so you can just change it and regenerate the STL. I think 1.5mm works reasonably well. You might also want to change, move or remove the cutouts for cables because you might not have cables in the same place.

comments.text: I'm sorry to hear about the trouble you had with the screws.  Have you ever been able to successfully print and use anything else that has a threads incorporated into the design?  I have printed this several times and never had a problem with the screws not fitting.  There have also been several other who have printed and used this with great success as well.  Could your machine be over extruding by chance?  Have you calibrated the e steps?  Calibrated the steps on the x, y and z axis motors?  If the calibration on your machine is off even a little, it could pose a problem with printing and using designs that have low tolerances like screws and threads.  If all else fails, you could try scaling the screws down by 2-3% and see if that helps.  Please let me know if you get it worked out.  Thanks!

comments.text: Interesting... These are designed to fit perfectly. You may have to work the screws back and forth a little (maybe even with some light oil) to get them to smoothen a little from some possible excess filament on the threads, but they should work fine after doing this. You said that you used some screws and nuts from Home Depot... what did you do with the nuts?  The screws here are intended to apply pressure to the ends of the X axis guide rods to keep tension off of the Z axis guide rods. Using nuts would likely take the pressure off the X axis rods and put it back on the Z axis, eliminating part of the functionality of this mod.

Base Frame is not included, it is available here from Hero (I am not associated) : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:445392

Duplicator I3 carriage upgrade : https://rapidlyprototyping.etsy.com

Final thoughts... I should have combined several pieces before hand (i.e. the upper leg is made up of 4 base blocks, and 4 cover pieces, I should have merged them all together to print as one instead of 8 pieces).. would have saved time.

title: DIY Prusa i3 x-end-idler and -motor for anit-backlash T8 brass nut

description.text:
This is a modification to Prusa's original MK2s x-end-idler and x-end-motor carriage mounts to fit the T8 Anti-backlash Brass Nut.

I tried to keep the # of file changes to a minimum, so only the 2 scad files, x-end-idler and x-end-motor, were modified.

This requires you to hacksaw 2 of the 4 mounting holes on the brass nut, to make them into open slots.

The opening on the x-end carriage for the brass nut is 12mm diameter to accommodate the anti-backlash spring+the brass nut.

I took into account the center-to-center distance of 17mm between z-rods & z-screw.

This worked perfectly for me with zero slop. Hope this works well for you too!

title: Thrustmaster Wheel Adapter - suit Ferrari 458 Challenge wheel/TX Base

description.text:
Adapter to allow you to fit an aftermarket wheel to the TX Racing Wheel with a Ferrari 458 Challenge wheel as a base. Includes paddle shift extensions and D-Pad extension/replacement

The 458 Challenge wheel has separate buttons and paddle shifters so is ideal to modify. To retain the D-Pad you will need to drill the replacement wheel. I used the adapter as a template then drill/file to suit.

Some hardware required -

  • Adapter is designed to accept M5 nuts. Wheels typically require M5 countersunk bolts.
  • Screws into wheel base are not long enough, I used 20mm M4 but you may get away with 15mm?
  • Paddle shifter extensions will accept M3 nut/bolts, I drilled the original paddles at 3.5mm and countersunk the extensions for flush finish.

Printing -

  • I printed in PLA at 95% infill to create a solid part. If you have tuned your extrusion 100% may be a better option.
  • The adapter is designed for the print to be paused, then drop the M5 nuts into the print, then recommence print. This locks the nuts in the print. The fit is deliberately loose to allow easy insertion, if you are quick this can be done without pausing print. I typically put a layer of masking tape on the top of the nuts, this allows the filament to bond to the nut a little better. In any case the print usually recovers in a few layers.

I have tested this for quite some time without issue. Assuming you have good layer bond the adapter should be strong enough.

D-Pad extension brings the D-Pad out flush with the new wheel position. Paddle shifter extension works well with 320mm wheel but I don't see any issues with slightly larger wheel.

description.text:
I have a friends and family that do a lot of crochet and knitting in their free time. One complaint they have is that it is hard to manage their different colored yarns when working on a multicolored project. The crochet (or knitting) ring lets you sort up to four different colored stings at your fingertips literally.

The ring is split into two parts as the actual ring can vary in size from person to person so there are different fits available. You can design your on custom fit if you like but I found that the 15 and 20 diameter sizes are okay for most people. The part that holds the string is designed so that you don't need to try and feed the string through the holes but instead slide it under the teeth at the mouth end and it should slide in place.

description.text:
This mainboard cover was designed in preparation for K8400 upgrade with silent drivers TMC2100. These drivers require good ventilation, that's why 80mm fan was placed inside the cover and is directly facing the mainboard. The cover can also be used with original VM8400DB drivers with DRV8825 chip as shown on attached images.

I used Evercool 80mm x 15mm DC 12V Ball Bearing Brushless, Low Noise Fan EC8015M12CA. You can replace it with any other 12V DC 80mm fan, but make sure its height does not exceed 15mm. This fan replaces the bottom fan that connects to FAN2 connector of the mainboard. The air should flow towards the mainboard.

The cover contains 5 separate printed parts and 2 metal mesh inserts. I cut out mesh from office set similar to one shown on the last image, but any 1mm thick metal mesh can be used.

Assembly

  • Disconnect printer from AC power (unplug the power cord).
  • Make sure 80mm fan has correct connector type.
  • Attach the fan to the top thing with four M5 x 12mm screws. Having fan guard is optional, but highly recommended.
  • Optionally install toggle switch into the hole in long_side2. It should connect to programming pins of the mainboard (JPROG). You will use it when flashing the firmware.
  • With eight M3 x 6mm screws attach short sides to the long sides. Slide in mesh inserts before tightening the screws. Mesh insert dimensions are 86mm x 32mm x 1mm.
  • Mount the mainboard and 4 sides of the cover to the bottom panel of the printer. Use four M3 x 16mm screws. The screw should go through the bottom panel, then spacer, then mainboard and end in the long_side hole. When mounting the mainboard make sure its power wires stay outside the cover.
  • Plug in toggle switch connector to the mainboard (JPROG).
  • Check all wire looms; make sure excess wires are outside the cover and not blocking airflow through meshes.
  • Plug in 80mm fan connector to the mainboard (FAN2) and attach the top with six M3 x 8mm screws.

I am not using reset button that came with K8400 because the printer has another one doing exactly the same. It is located above SD card slot.

As you can see from the images I relocated the power supply (as part of another upgrade), but the cover should fit just fine when the power supply is at its original position.

This is not a real Thing that you'd want to bother with. It's just a conceptual test of an oddball idea. It seems to work, but that's with the odd configuration of my printer which is probably completely different from anyone else's old Replicator. It was made to use some of the stuff I had on hand, which again, certainly won't match the stuff you have on hand.

Anyway, it's here just to add to the community knowledge - I've given it a try so you don't have to, should you have the urge. OTOH, it does work... so some deranged individual might want to try something similar.

So I had this centrifugal blower fan on hand. It's much larger than fans typically used for print coolers, with those fans always being mounted on the carriage. I also happened to have a CPAP mask hose. [FYI a CPAP is one of those breathing machines that people with sleep apnia use to prevent snoring (and death)] The CPAP hose is lightweight, very flexible, and smooth inside for unimpeded airflow. It also has a nice pliable rubber connector on one end, and the other end is a neet plastic swivel. So, why not a blower mounted on the back of the printer, and a flex hose to the print cooling duct on the carriage?

My replicator is a dual extruder version, but I only have the right extruder mounted. The duct I have here won't work with both extruders mounted, but a duct could be worked out to accommodate both if necessary. This duct mounts with one of the tall center carriage screws, and also supplies a cable mounting point. There's also another screw location that just supplies a friction point so the duct doesn't swivel. It would be simpler to mount the duct to the cold bar with the left extruder mounting holes, but I usually had the left fan mounted there for extra cold bar cooling. The swivel end of the CPAP hose just friction fits into the duct, and that's all it needs - it stays in place nicely even with the carriage in motion.

Note that this is a CPAP mask hose, not the main hose. It's much smaller than the main hose and is a perfect length. Don't have a hose? Ask around. Lots of people use CPAP's, and the hoses are usually replaced every six months or so.

The fan mount just slips onto the top plate at the back of the printer and is secured with a single screw. The fan just screws onto the mount. The fan-hose adapter is just a slip fit on the fan, and the rubber end of the hose is just a slip fit too. It all stays in place nicely. I have a large acrylic hood that fits over the entire top of the printer, so the hose, fan, and the fan mount are entirely enclosed in the heated chamber.

The hose just needs a single zip tie to the carriage cables. It follows along nicely with little to no extra force on the carriage, and doesn't interfere with anything in the chamber.

The blower I had was 12V, which wasn't a problem for me as I have a 12V supply mounted in the base of the printer (along with a 24V supply). I run the 12V thru a cheap speed control so I can adjust the airflow down. Holding it up to my face it feels like a pretty good breeze, so I know I've got some fiddling to do to find the flow necessary.

It's manual now of course, so I need to see what's available for g-code control. I seem to recall that the MightyBoard isn't too swift in that respect.

The duct is really clunky and needs rework both in both the airflow and mounting aspects. It does approximately direct the airflow towards the print just below the nozzle, but I'm sure it could be better.
